</style>) and one which memorises the training dataset ( <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="C_{\text{mem}}"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-msubsup"><span class="mjx-base" style="margin-right: -0.045em;"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.519em; padding-bottom: 0.298em; padding-right: 0.045em;">C</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sub" style="font-size: 70.7%; vertical-align: -0.212em; padding-right: 0.071em;"><span class="mjx-texatom" style=""><span class="mjx-mrow"><span class="mjx-mtext"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">mem</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ). The key insight is that <i>when there are multiple circuits that achieve strong training performance, weight decay prefers circuits with high &quot;efficiency&quot;</i> , that is, circuits that require less parameter norm to produce a given logit value.</p><p> Efficiency answers our question above: if <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="C_{\text{gen}}"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-msubsup"><span class="mjx-base" style="margin-right: -0.045em;"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.519em; padding-bottom: 0.298em; padding-right: 0.045em;">C</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sub" style="font-size: 70.7%; vertical-align: -0.212em; padding-right: 0.071em;"><span class="mjx-texatom" style=""><span class="mjx-mrow"><span class="mjx-mtext"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.519em;">gen</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is more efficient than <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="C_{\text{mem}}"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-